\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator indicated that Criteria 1 and 5 are in need of improvement. The evaluator stated that this is a teaching qualification. The name of the qualification is incorrect and it should be an Advanced Certificate in FET Mathematics Literacy Teaching.\line \line The evaluator noted that in presenting this ACE\'2C the institution will provide the means to develop the competence of teachers to teach mathematics that will take place within the philosophical and moral framework expressed in the mission and vision of the institution. The evaluator thought that the rationale of the proposed programme is sound and in line with the needs of the country regarding  mathematics teachers. The evaluator\'2C however\'2C raises a number of concerns regarding Criterion 1. First\'2C the coherence in the design of this qualification is not clear and needs to be explained. It is for example not clear how year 1 modules \'28pure maths literacy modules\'29 are related to the modules in the second year where the focus is on pedagogy and mathematics. The question that needs to be answered is whether these mathematics literacy content-related modules will be presented within the epistemological framework envisaged in the second year modules.\line \line Secondly\'2C the content of the pure mathematics literacy modules is of concern.  The content is strictly aligned with the learning outcomes \'28and content\'29 as portrayed in the NCS \'28not with the new CAPS document\'29. The institution provided no explanation on how these mathematics literacy modules will be presented on NQF level 6.  Thirdly\'2C the prescribed textbooks are mostly school text books and FET vocational textbooks. This implies that it will be a challenge to offer these modules on a level above NQF level 4. Finally\'2C the number of credits presented in year 1 add up to 51 and in the case of year 2 it adds up to 69 and not 60 as indicated.\line \line In terms of Criterion 5\'2C the evaluator pointed out that in the purpose of the programme the importance of pedagogical content knowledge is emphasized\'2C but it is not evident how the different knowledge\'2C namely subject factual knowledge\'2C the curriculum knowledge and the pedagogical knowledge will be integrated so that the pedagogical knowledge can materialize. The knowledge mix is a further indication of the lack of coherence. Various types of learning can take place within modules and are not necessarily restricted to a specific module.\line \line The evaluator also indicated that more data on where prospective students will perform WIL must be provided. \line In addition\'2C no evidence was submitted to support the integration of instructional and learning technology. This needs to be spelled out\'2C especially in the teaching of the year 1 modules \'28the pure maths literacy modules\'29. More evidence is needed. \line Given the concerns raised\'2C the Directorate cannot support the provisional accreditation of the programme and therefore recommends non accreditation.\line \line \line \cell \pard 

